{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"e2edac3b-1539-4725-94c5-872abf783e94","content":"You're on MSTest 3.8.2 which supports constructor injection for `TestContext`. Here's the recommended pattern:\n\n```csharp\n[TestClass]\npublic class MyTests\n{\n    private readonly TestContext _testContext;\n\n    // Constructor injection for TestContext (MSTest 3.2+)\n    public MyTests(TestContext testContext)\n    {\n        _testContext = testContext;\n        // Synchronous initialization here\n    }\n\n    // Async initialization runs after constructor\n    [TestInitialize]\n    public async Task SetupAsync()\n    {\n        // Asynchronous initialization here\n        await SomeServiceAsync();\n    }\n\n    [TestMethod]\n    public void MyTest()\n    {\n        _testContext.WriteLine(\"Test is running\");\n        Assert.IsTrue(true);\n    }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n- **Constructor** — use for synchronous setup and receiving `TestContext` via injection (available since MSTest 3.2).\n- **`[TestInitialize]`** — use for `async` setup that needs awaiting. Runs before each test, after the constructor.\n- The older `public TestContext TestContext { get; set; }` property approach still works but constructor injection is preferred in modern MSTest.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"6524ff0c-92dc-477b-826d-29ab37d8d52f","outputTokens":295,"requestId":"E440:30C599:33973FB:391511B:6A02FB74"},"id":"7cd132b1-080e-4e4e-97bf-c1277121c1bd","timestamp":"2026-05-12T10:05:53.207Z","parentId":"43a10ece-b81e-4330-8b26-72f1ccfe7ba6"}
